Europe needs a migration reboot
Brussels — Over 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
At the same time, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching all summer for a safe port where their passengers can disembark.
The refugee and migrant camps on Lesbos Island in Greece are overcrowded, and the conditions in other安置 camps in Libya are similarly dire.
Turkey has revoked the 2016 agreement that prevented migrants from entering the EU.
Although Europe wants to help migrants and respects international law, it does not want to be overcrowded.
In 2015–16, the number of refugees and migrants entering the EU surged — many fleeing the war in Syria — which greatly affected trust among EU member states.
The massive influx of migrants eroded governments' confidence in the EU's external border and asylum management, and also highlighted the ineffectiveness of cooperation with migrant-sending countries.
Therefore, migration has become a political football and a favorite tool of populists.
Under the leadership of President von der Leyen, the new European Commission must regain control over migration issues while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
For this reason, the EU needs to revise its policies in four areas and mobilize member states to take action for the benefit of Europe.
First, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, which is a prerequisite for maintaining open internal borders.
Any country in which people can move freely within its territory, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, would not outsource control of its external borders to a state or region.
Controlling the EU's external borders must be a collective task, as well as a national task.
The European Border and Coast Guard Agency, Frontex, must be further strengthened and should deploy joint patrols — including along coastlines and airports — with member states.
The EU must also restart Operation Sophia to combat illegal immigration in the Mediterranean.
Second, Europe needs to handle economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Grouping them together has already led the asylum system to the brink of collapse; handling them separately would help ensure that migrants concerned about their safety can voice their concerns under protected rights.
Solving the EU's real economic and social needs requires an effective blue card or green card policy targeting economic migrants, and the implementation of an overall immigration quota.
This cannot wait for the next migration crisis to introduce these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboo.
First, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a matter of common interest.
Second, the policy must clearly define which migrants are welcome.
Third, member states must answer what kind of EU assistance is needed to achieve a smooth migration process.
Finally, visas and work permits must be made transparent to facilitate the return of illegal migrants to their countries of origin.
Indeed, according to the EU treaties, each member state is required to manage migration from outside the EU on its own.
However, reaching an agreement on the overall EU immigration quota would be a significant step forward.
In turn, member states can specify the countries of origin and specific requirements for the economic migrants they wish to admit, as well as the EU budget resources required to accommodate them.
In this way, the right to accept migrants would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has long implemented an active immigration policy, selecting immigrants based on criteria such as country of origin, skill level, and age group.
Europe can do the same.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First, the one-size-fits-all approach to forcibly distributing asylum seekers within the EU must be abandoned.
This requirement has undermined the atmosphere within the EU, but it could still be feasible if the border, asylum, and immigration systems are fully effective.
Furthermore, one cannot expect the EU's frontline member states to solve the issue of illegal migration crossing external borders alone.
Refugee camps are overcrowded, and migrants are subjected to abuse by authorities or pushed northward.
The responsibility of the first member state of arrival must be supplemented by the EU's cohesion policy.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to improve the conduct and management capacity of national asylum authorities.
Only in this way can national decisions be respected throughout the Schengen Area, ensuring the integrity of the cross-border travel zone.
After improving the conduct and management capacity of national asylum authorities, the processing procedures for asylum applications can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should build stronger win-win cooperation with source countries and transit countries.
To repatriate migrants who are legally prohibited from entering the EU back to their countries of origin, these links are essential.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic policy tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as plans in the areas of security, trade, energy, agriculture, fishing, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's immigration targets and skill cooperation to prepare for European jobs can be offered to third countries seeking stable remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes population explosions in Sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of disease; ethnic conflicts; and a lack of job opportunities.
The EU's aid should focus on restoring stability and reducing risks by supporting security, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in this area could make investments safer, unlock private and domestic finance, thereby achieving national economic growth, job creation, and providing alternatives to migration.
The new European Commission has the opportunity to move the EU away from an unconscious reaction to the migration crisis toward a more coherent and consistent approach, regardless of internal or external matters.
We must never miss this opportunity.
